children.label: Eurasia
children.definition: The large land mass comprising the continents of Europe and Asia.

children.label: Sudan
children.definition: A country in Northeastern Africa, formerly known as Anglo-Egyptian Sudan. It's capital is Khartoum.

children.label: South Sudan
children.definition: A nation located in East-Central Africa; south of Sudan, north of Uganda and Kenya, west of Ethiopia. Independence from Sudan was attained on 9 July 2011. The capital is Juba.

Land Between the Lakes National Recreation Area

George Washington and Jefferson National Forests

Territory of Christmas Island
children.definition: An island in the Indian Ocean, located at 10° 30' S latitude and 105 40 E longitude, which is a territory of Australia.

children.label: Samoa
children.definition: A group of islands in the SW Pacific Ocean divided into American Samoa (administered by the U.S. Department of Interior) and Western Samoa (an independant country)

children.label: Borneo
children.definition: An island in the Malay Archipelago forming part of Malaysia in the northern region and part of Indonesia in the southern region.

children.label: New Guinea
children.definition: An island in the west Pacific Ocean divided into Irian Jaya (Indonesia) and Papua New Guinea (independent from 1975, formerly an United Nations trust territory).

children.label: Caspian Sea
children.definition: The largest inland body of water, located between Asia and Europe.

children.label: Sargasso Sea
children.definition: Large tract of still water in the middle of the North Atlantic Ocean that is predominated by Sargassum seaweed.

children.label: Caribbean Sea
children.definition: The Caribbean Sea is located at 9 to 22ºN and 89 to 60ºW. The countries found to the south of the Caribbean Sea are Venezuela, Colombia, and Panama. The countries found to the west are Costa Rica, Nicaragua, Honduras, Guatemala, Belize, and the Yucatan Peninsula of Mexico. The countries found to the north are the Greater Antilles Islands of Cuba, Hispaniola, Jamaica, and Puerto Rico. The Lesser Antilles Islands are found to the east.

children.label: Pacific Rim
children.definition: The coastal regions bordering the Pacific Ocean.

children.label: Mid-Atlantic region
children.definition: Region on the East Coast of the United States, including Delaware, District of Columbia, Maryland, New Jersey, New York, and Pennsylvania.

children.label: Finger Lakes region
children.definition: The area in western New York State around a group of long narrow lakes, including lakes Seneca, Cayuga, Keuka, Canandaigua, Owasco and Skaneateles.

children.label: Micronesia
children.definition: One of the three main divisions of Pacific Ocean Islands, in the west Pacific Ocean, north of the equator. The principal island groups include the Caroline Islands, Nauru, Kiribati, the Northern Mariana Islands, and the Marshall Islands.

children.label: Great Basin States
children.definition: The elevated region between the Wasatch and Sierra Nevada Mountains.

children.label: Scandinavia
children.definition: A region encompassing Denmark, Norway, and Sweden, sometimes expanded to include Finland and Iceland.

children.label: Alps region
children.definition: Large mountain system of south-central Europe extending through Italy, France, Switzerland, Germany, Austria and the northwest Balkan peninsula.

children.label: Baltic States
children.definition: The countries of Estonia, Latvia and Lithuania on the east shore of the Baltic Sea.

children.label: Prairie Pothole region
children.definition: A wetland region encompassing the Northern Great Plains region from the upper Midwest and extending into Canada. The region has large shallow depressions that were created by retreating glaciers and has wetlands that are either temporary, seasonal, or permanent in nature.

children.label: Amazonia
children.definition: The region immediately surrounding the Amazon River in South America.

children.label: Great Lakes region
children.definition: Region in North America, surrounding the five Great Lakes (Superior, Michigan, Huron, Erie, Ontario).

children.label: Cascade Mountain region
children.definition: Region in North America, extending from northeast California (north continuation of the Sierra Nevada Mountains) across Oregon and Washington. Its continuation into Canada is known as the Coast Mountains. Mount Rainier is the highest peak in the region.

children.label: Corn Belt region
children.definition: Region in the Midwestern United States where is maize is grown on a vast scale, covering Illinois, Indiana, Iowa, Minnesota, Nebraska, and Ohio.

children.label: Intermountain West region
children.definition: The inland area from the Rocky Mountains to the Sierra Nevada and Cascades mountains and from southern Canada to northern New Mexico and Arizona.

children.label: Appalachian region
children.definition: Region in North America, extending from Newfoundland to central Alabama. (In the United States, includes areas of Alabama, Georgia, Kentucky, Maryland, New York, North Carolina, Ohio, Pennsylvania, South Carolina, Tennessee, Virginia and West Virginia).

children.label: Blue Ridge Mountain region
children.definition: The eastern and southeastern area of the Appalachian Mountain Region which encompasses the Great Smoky Mountains and extends from Pennsylvania to north Georgia.

children.label: Cumberland Mountain region
children.definition: An area in the southeastern section of the Appalachian Mountain Region located in Virginia, Kentucky, and Tennessee.

children.label: Allegheny Mountain region
children.definition: Mountain area that is part of the Appalachian Mountain region which is west of and generally runs parallel to the Blue Ridge Mountain Region.

children.label: Great Smoky Mountain region
children.definition: An area of the Appalachian Mountain region that extends along the border of North Carolina and Tennessee.

children.label: Ozarks
children.definition: An area of low mountains in northwestern Arkansas, southeastern Missouri and northeastern Oklahoma.

children.label: Black Hills region
children.definition: A mountainous area in western South Dakota and northeast Wyoming.

children.label: Maghreb
children.definition: Region of Northwestern Africa including Morocco, Algeria, Tunisia and sometimes Libya.

children.label: Blue Mountain region (Oregon)
children.definition: A mountain range in northeast Oregon and southeast Washington.

children.label: Central Valley of California
children.definition: The large fertile region in the interior of California that lies between the coastal mountains and the Sierra Nevada moutain range.

children.label: Persian Gulf States
children.definition: A term commonly applied to a number of states on the east coast of the Arabian Pennisula.

children.label: Melanesia
children.definition: One of the three main divisions of Pacific Ocean Islands, in the southwest Pacific Ocean, northeast of Australia and south of the equator. It includes the Solomon Islands, Vanatu, Tuvalu, New Caledonia, Fiji.

children.label: El Gran Chaco
children.definition: A vast plain with varied environment and climatic zones that extends through northern Argentina, southeastern Bolivia, northwestern Paraguay and into a small area of southwestern Brazil. Land uses include wildlife habitat, livestock and crop production and forestry.

children.label: Adirondacks
children.definition: An area around the Adirondack Mountains located in northern New York State and sometimes included as part of the Appalachian region.

children.label: Gulf of Mexico region
children.definition: Region in the Southern United States surrounding the Gulf of Mexico, (including the states of Alabama, Florida, Louisiana, Mississippi, and Texas).

children.label: Rocky Mountain region
children.definition: Region in North America, extending from the Arctic region in Canada south towards the Mexican frontier. (In the United States, includes areas of Arizona, New Mexico, Colorado, Utah, Nevada, Wyoming, Idaho and Montana).

children.label: New England region
children.definition: Region in Northeast section of the United States, including Connecticut, Maine, Massachusetts, New Hampshire, Rhode Island, and Vermont.

children.label: Pampas region
children.definition: An extensive, flat and fertile grassland of temperate South America east of the Andes and mostly in Argentina and extending into Uruguay. The vast plains are some of the riches grazing areas in the world. The temperate climate and fertile soils are conducive for cultivation.

children.label: Caribbean
children.definition: The region including the Caribbean Sea, its islands, and the countries on its Central and/or South American coasts.

children.label: Polynesia
children.definition: One of the three main divisions of Pacific Ocean Islands, in the central and south Pacific Ocean. The principal island groups include the Hawaiian islands, Samoa, and the islands of French Polynesia.

children.label: Mississippi Delta region
children.definition: Region in the Southeastern United States surrounding the lower Mississippi River, including areas of Arkansas, Mississippi and Louisiana.

children.label: Middle East
children.definition: An extensive region comprising the countries of southwest Asia and northeast Africa

children.label: Australasian region
children.definition: Region generally including the islands of the southwest Pacific Ocean, Australia, New Zealand, New Guinea and the Malay Archipelago.

children.label: Great Plains region
children.definition: Region in North America, extending from the Laurentian Highlands in Canada to Texas.

children.label: Balkans
children.definition: Countries occupying the Balkan Peninsula.

children.label: Pantanal
children.definition: An immense freshwater wetland system of South America situated along the Paraguay River and its tributaries.

children.label: Lapland
children.definition: A region of extreme northern Europe including northern Norway, Sweden, Finland and Russia. It is largely within the Arctic Circle.

children.label: Andes region
children.definition: The area of the great mountain system of South America, extending 4500 miles along the entire west coast of South America from Tierra del Fuego in the south to Panama in the north and crossing through the countries of Venezuela, Bolivia, Ecuador, Colombia, Peru, Chile and Argentina. The Andes region is made up of several parallel ranges, called cordilleras.

children.label: Latin America
children.definition: Collectively, those countries in the Western Hemisphere in which the predominant language is a Romance (French, Spanish, Portuguese) language.

children.label: Sierra Nevada (California)
children.definition: A 400 mile long mountain range located in eastern California.

children.label: Central Valley of California
children.definition: The large fertile region in the interior of California that lies between the coastal mountains and the Sierra Nevada moutain range.

children.label: Borneo
children.definition: An island in the Malay Archipelago forming part of Malaysia in the northern region and part of Indonesia in the southern region.

children.label: Timor
children.definition: An island in the west Pacific Ocean divided into Indonesia and East Timor (independent since 2002, formerly part of Indonesia).

children.label: Ireland
children.definition: An island surrounded by the North Atlantic, Irish and Celtic Seas, comprised of Northern Ireland (part of the United Kingdom) in the northwest part of the island, and the Irish Republic in the remaining area.

children.label: Cabo Verde
children.definition: A country in western Africa composed of a group of islands in the North Atlantic Ocean, west of Senegal. The capital is Praia.

children.label: Hispaniola
children.definition: An island in the north central Caribbean Sea, east of Cuba, divided between the republic of Haiti on the west and the Dominican Republic on the east.

children.label: South Georgia and South Sandwich Islands
Virgin Islands of the United States
